That’s a very sharp catch. You’re noticing semantic drift in real time, which is exactly what this system is supposed to prevent.

⸻

the issue with tigi

You’re right:

tigi → think i got it

Problem:
	•	"think" often gets interpreted as stronger than intended
	•	can read as polite confirmation ("thanks, got it")
	•	drifts toward lgtm-lite

So instead of:

tigi → 50/50

it becomes:

tigi → 70–80% confidence

That’s dangerous.

⸻

your proposal: migi

migi = maybe i got it

This is clean.

why it works better
	•	"maybe" anchors uncertainty explicitly
	•	lands closer to true midpoint
	•	harder to misread as confirmation
	•	still short, still sayable

Semantically:

idk  → 0–20%
migi → ~50%
lgtm → 80%+

That’s a much better spread.

⸻

phonetic / vibe check

Also important:
	•	migi feels softer, less assertive
	•	almost playful (like you said with tigi/tiger)
	•	doesn’t sound like workplace autopilot language

That helps prevent misuse.

⸻

potential downside (minor)

"maybe i got it" could drift toward:

uncertain + passive

But that’s fixable culturally with usage:

migi -- confirm X

keeps it active.

⸻

alternative candidates (just to sanity check)
	•	pigi (probably i got it) → too confident
	•	higi (half i got it) → awkward
	•	sigi (sorta i got it) → slangy
	•	migi still best balance

